INSERT INTO `tbl_projects` (`project_id`, `sector_id`, `title`, `description`, `image`, `slug`, `created_date`, `updated_date`, `status`, `url`, `meta_description`, `meta_keyword`, `project_position`) VALUES
(1, 1, 'Hyderabad International Airport - Greenfield Airport', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%">\r\n	Hyderabad International Airport is the country&rsquo;s premier PPP Airport. STUP played an integral and major role in the team which conceived the entire airport master plan of Hyderabad international Airport Limited (HIAL). The airport is rated today amongst the top 5 airports in the world for its capacity and was designed and constructed in a record timeframe of 3.5 years.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%">\r\n	The site covers approximately 2,000 hectares. The master plan is developed in 4 phases for&nbsp; an ultimate&nbsp; capacity&nbsp; of&nbsp; 40&nbsp; million&nbsp; passengers&nbsp; per annum, which is expected&nbsp; to be reached&nbsp; in 2050. Phase - I has been planned to handle&nbsp; 10 million passengers&nbsp; per annum and&nbsp; 100,000&nbsp; tons&nbsp; of&nbsp; cargo&nbsp;&nbsp; per&nbsp; annum,&nbsp; both&nbsp;&nbsp; figures expected&nbsp; to be reached in 2020. The project also involves construction of Information&nbsp; Technology&nbsp; Parks&nbsp; and Business&nbsp; Parks&nbsp; to&nbsp; be&nbsp; developed&nbsp;&nbsp; in&nbsp; the&nbsp; vicinity&nbsp; of&nbsp; the proposed&nbsp; airport.&nbsp; Phase I required 100,000 m<sup>2</sup> passenger terminal in two levels designed to handle passengers and a 10,000 m<sup>2</sup> cargo terminal.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n', '14225261471.jpg', 'hyderabad-international-airport-greenfield-airport-1', '2015-01-05 11:58:25', '2015-01-29 16:54:15', '1', '', '', 'HIAL Night Photo', 1),
(2, 1, 'New Doha International Airport', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%">\r\n	A site of approximately 1,700 hectares, located just to the east of the existing airport, has been designated for the development of New Doha International Airport and required some land reclamation.&nbsp; The airport is to be the home base and hub of Qatar Airways. STUP was engaged by Aeroports de Paris to prepare the architectural, engineering and MEP design and details for 40 aviation related structures and also carry out the civil engineering for the airside infrastructure works based on the concept.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n', '14223437150.jpg', 'new-doha-international-airport', '2015-01-05 11:59:52', '2015-01-29 16:57:49', '1', '', '', '', 2),
(3, 1, 'Bangalore International Airport', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%">\r\n	The project envisages the expansion of the current terminal from 11.40 Million Passengers per Annum (MPPA) to 17.20 MPPA. T1 will be extended&nbsp; by three grids (3 x 24m) on East and West sides&nbsp; along&nbsp; with an&nbsp; East&nbsp; pier&nbsp; for&nbsp; a&nbsp; total&nbsp; area&nbsp; of 135,165 m<sup>2</sup> (including the existing&nbsp; building) on 4 levels: basement, ground and&nbsp; levels 1 &amp; 2. Preparation of Master plan for various utilities including power, telecommunications and IT, water supply and fire fighting, sewerage system, storm water drainage and rain water harvesting techniques, aviation fuel, solid waste management, piped natural gas (PNG), energy management system (EMS), traffic and circulation etc. for Airside and city side.&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n', '14223439051.jpg', 'bangalore-international-airport', '2015-01-05 12:01:48', '2015-01-29 16:57:25', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(4, 1, 'Passenger Terminal Building At Benghazi Airport', '<p class="MsoBodyText" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:\r\n.2in;margin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;\r\nmso-para-margin-bottom:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;\r\nline-height:120%">\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:11.0pt;line-height:120%;\r\nfont-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold">Libyan Civil Aviation Authority is constructing a Passenger Terminal Building in Bengazi Airport and the built up area is 80,000 sqm. The scope includes preliminary and detailed design of the structural and mechanical work, and specifications. STUP is also doing the detailed design of the architectural work and reports of the terminal building for Aeroports de Paris Ingenieurs, Paris. The terminal is conceived with a complex roof structure in&nbsp; a large birdlike shell incorporating skylights. The sweeping aerodynamic roof is the signature element in the design of this prestigious terminal building.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14212354061.jpg', 'passenger-terminal-building-at-benghazi-airport', '2015-01-05 12:02:35', '2015-01-29 16:41:44', '1', '', '', '', 3),
(5, 1, 'Passenger Terminal Building At Sebha Airport', '<p class="MsoBodyText" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:\r\n.2in;margin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;\r\nmso-para-margin-bottom:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;\r\nline-height:120%">\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:11.0pt;line-height:120%;\r\nfont-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold">Libyan Civil Aviation Authority is constructing a Passenger Terminal Building in Sheba Airport and the built up area of the building is 60,000 sqm. The scope includes preliminary and detailed design of the structural and mechanical work, and specifications. STUP is also doing the detailed design of the architectural work and reports of the terminal building for Aeroports de Paris Ingenieurs, Paris. The architecture involves and expressive structural system with&nbsp; lightwells and hyperbolic paraboloids, with ample daylighting and greenery in this futuristic modular design.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223439710.jpg', 'passenger-terminal-building-at-sebha-airport', '2015-01-05 12:03:04', '2015-01-29 16:41:54', '1', '', '', '', 4),
(132, 2, 'IIM, Ahmedabad, Expansion', '<p>\r\n	This competition winning project envisages the expansion project of the Indian Institute of Management designed by the legendary architect Louis Kahn.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The expansion of this complex involves the design of residential facilities and a student activity centre housing 320 students.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The project draws inspiration from Louis Kahn&rsquo;s rhythms of repetitions. &nbsp;While using the modular units and a play of light and volumes the design creates unique shaded spaces in a tight urban context.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The rooms are tightly around private courtyards eliminating visual obstruction and ensuring privacy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The student activity centre is located at the podium of the building and accessed by an angular staircase, which led to entrance of the structure above the podium.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The play of light and the creation of intimate and social spaces form the central theme of this contextual response to the architecture of the existing IIM campus.</p>', '14220748500.jpg', 'iim-ahmedabad-expansion', '2015-01-24 10:17:30', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(131, 2, 'Parliament Building for the Gambia ', '<p>\r\n	This green building designed house the Parliament of The Gambia located in west Africa . It has been conceived as an iconic and symbolic building. &nbsp;The curved roof represent s the flow of the river Gambia and Golden CONE houses the assembly hall representing the orange flame of hope &nbsp;an important theme depicted in the countries banner. The Green embankments represent the agriculture which forms the sustenance of this river line country. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The design envisages naturally ventilated and cool space sand public areas, it maximizes the entry of indirect light through devices such as skylights and internal courts and the innovative perforated shading screens of the assembly hall. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	This small project for this little country involves the challenge of the conception of an Iconic and signature building with its sweeping curve, environmental sky-frame roof, and use of sustainable and green design strategies.&nbsp;</p>', '14220747841.jpg', 'parliament-building-for-the-gambia', '2015-01-24 10:16:24', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(81, 7, 'Central Secretariat Station (Entrance), New Delhi', '<p>\r\n	This is the starting point of The Central Secretariat &ndash; Badarpur Corridor of Delhi MRTS and of length 0.686KM which consist of the underground New Central Secretariat Station (close to the existing Central Secretariat Station on Line-2 in operation) of length 240 m and tunnel of length 446 m. The work consist of design and drawing of the Station and the tunnel along with associated structures such as Entry/ Exit Structure, utilities Galleries, AC Plant room, pump house , Diesel Generator Room etc. One of the main features of the project is to facilitate the connecting arrangement between the existing and the proposed station at two levels i.e at Platform level and the concourse level by breaking the wall of the existing station.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	This station is located in a very sensitive location near Parliament and a narrow strip of approximately 40 m is available with KrishiBhavan on one side and the existing station on the other side and the total construction was done by Cut &amp; Cover Method. All the temporary retaining structural works with soldier piles and struts associated with the construction of works including the temporary decking over cut &amp; cover structures under roadways to allow uninterrupted flow of traffic also part of the Project.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Owner : Delhi Metro Rail Corporation</p>', '14219461103.jpg', 'central-secretariat-station-(entrance)-new-delhi', '2015-01-22 22:31:50', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(13, 1, 'Indian Airlines Hangar at Santacruz Airport, Mumbai', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%;mso-layout-grid-align:\r\nnone;text-autospace:none">\r\n	This hangar can service 2 Airbus 300s and 8 Caravelles simultaneously. It has a prestressed concrete folded plate roof with stayed cantilevers of 62.3 m span on either side of the 27.4 m wide central service complex. The<span style="mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;color:#231F20;mso-bidi-language:MR"> balanced cantilever roof has thin prestressed concrete folded plates and back stays. The extremely light structure has an average concrete thickness of just 200mm. The overall length between cantilever tips is 152m, its width 91.4m and height 15.9m.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%;mso-layout-grid-align:\r\nnone;text-autospace:none">\r\n	<span style="mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;color:#231F20;\r\nmso-bidi-language:MR">The thin roof of 200mm was built with M45 concrete and was developed by STUP without the use of plasticizers.&nbsp; It is an internationally acclaimed structure and i</span>n 1970 the stayed cantilever roof held a world record for a stayed concrete structure.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n', '14223440190.jpg', 'indian-airlines-hangar-at-santacruz-airport-mumbai', '2015-01-13 12:41:24', '2015-01-29 16:42:15', '1', '', '', '', 5),
(14, 1, 'Air India Boeing 747 Hangar at Santacruz  Airport, Mumbai', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%;mso-layout-grid-align:\r\nnone;text-autospace:none">\r\n	<span style="mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;color:#231F20;\r\nmso-bidi-language:MR">The 96.6m long structural steel cantilever roof of the hangar is designed to house 747 Jumbo Jets. The highest point of the roof is located 32.3m above ground level to accommodate the tail of the aircraft and overhead equipment. The cantilever structure is anchored to rock by means of specially coated corrosion-proof prestressed anchors for which 24mm diameter 8 cables have been used.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%">\r\n	The roof is a structural steel cantilever truss suspended by structural steel stays, struts and back-stays which can all function under stress reversals. The clear stayed cantilever is 78 m.&nbsp; It was a world record, at that time, for this type of cantilever roof.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n', '14223440580.jpg', 'air-india-boeing-747-hangar-at-santacruz-airport-mumbai', '2015-01-13 12:42:32', '2015-01-29 16:42:24', '1', '', '', '', 6),
(15, 1, 'Agatti Airport, Lakshadweep ', '<p class="MsoBodyText" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:\r\n.2in;margin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;\r\nmso-para-margin-bottom:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;\r\nline-height:120%">\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:11.0pt;line-height:120%;\r\nfont-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;">The proposed project is the Development and Modernization of Agatti Airport. The runaway strip, 335m x 192m wide, is to be built on an RCC platform in the sea. The platform will also accommodate apron, terminal building, ATC, technical building and fire station etc. This Coral Reef Island does not permit reclamation and the RCC platform will minimise environmental damage. The Passenger Terminal is designed to complement the serene atmosphere in Agatti Island and is a prefabricated large span hyperboloid structure with skylights providing a column free interior hall. The fa&ccedil;ade is pre-dominantly glass to provide a clear view of the scenic lagoon to the passengers. The building is a single level terminal and is designed for 75 Arriving Pax and 75 Departing Pax. with expansion capacity for 150 Arriving Pax and 150 Departing Pax. The overall area of the Passenger Terminal is 2950 sqm.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223441802.jpg', 'agatti-airport-lakshadweep', '2015-01-13 12:43:34', '2015-03-03 12:24:17', '1', '', '', '', 7),
(16, 1, 'Modernisation and Upgradation of Helibase at Juhu', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%">\r\n	The offshore operation of the ONGC is heavily dependent on the Juhu Helibase since the manpower for the rig operation is taken from here to the high sea. The upgradation will ensure uninterrupted operations throughout the year by raising the existing hangar floor level, rerouting and raising the access road, raising the apron level above the High Flood Level. The project involves consolidating the existing scattered facilities into one single annex building and constructing an additional ATF facility. The scope includes Concept Design, Detailed Architectural Design and Drawings, Detailed Structural Design, Electrical Engineering, Ventilation and Air Conditioning. The futuristic terminal building is designed with an aerodynamic architecture using maximum daylight and internal courts to enhance the ambience.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n', '14223441140.jpg', 'modernisation-and-upgradation-of-helibase-at-juhu', '2015-01-13 12:45:18', '2015-01-29 16:42:37', '1', '', '', '', 8),
(17, 1, 'Hangar Building, Hal Helicopter Factory Complex, Bangalore', '<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-top:.2in;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:.2in;\r\nmargin-left:0in;mso-para-margin-top:1.2gd;mso-para-margin-right:0in;mso-para-margin-bottom:\r\n1.2gd;mso-para-margin-left:0in;text-align:justify;line-height:120%;mso-layout-grid-align:\r\nnone;text-autospace:none">\r\n	<span style="mso-bidi-font-family:Calibri;color:#231F20;\r\nmso-bidi-language:MR">This hangar building covers an area of 74m x 63m in plan. The central two storeyed complex is flanked by cantilever hangars measuring 32.5m on either side. The roof structure is a continuous multiple folded plate system in reinforced concrete. The hangers are suspended by prestressed concrete ties which meet the triangulation formed by the inclined pylons and the roof of the central complex.STUP was engaged in conceiving and designing the entire masterplan and facilities of the HAL complex in Bangalore which contains many signature buildings.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223441450.jpg', 'hangar-building-hal-helicopter-factory-complex-bangalore', '2015-01-13 12:46:14', '2015-01-29 16:42:43', '1', '', '', '', 9),
(18, 10, 'GHATAPRABHA RIGHT BANK CANAL PROJECT, KARNATAKA', '<p align="left" class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">Ghataprabha Right Bank Canal (GRBC) is one of the three components in Ghataprabha Project running for a length of 202 km irrigating about 9000 hectares of lands in Belgaum and Bagalkot districts of Karnataka. The scope of work included detailed engineering, comprehensive network plan and detailed final location survey of GRBC main canal of 82 km length. The project involved construction of various cross drainage and head works of about 450 nos, such as single and double lane road bridges, aqueducts, super passage, canal syphons, cross regulators, head regulator, box culverts, adjustable proportionate and open flume modular type outlets, and vertical drops. The main canal is lined with plain cement concrete. Berms are provided at every 6.0m in deep cutting<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223609790.jpg', 'ghataprabha-right-bank-canal-project-karnataka', '2015-01-13 14:45:03', '2015-01-27 17:46:19', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(19, 10, 'BHIMA AQUEDUCT, MAHARASHTRA', '<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%">The Bhima aqueduct was constructed by the Government of Maharashtra to irrigate drought prone areas of Sholapur district. The aqueduct, with a discharge of 42.5 cumecs, is 947m in length with a 3.5m roadway and continuous spans of 41.5m. The aqueduct is supported on 23 tall, slender, hollow circular piers 40m high, constructed with climbing forms. The truncated circular cross section which is 4.8m in diameter achieves high hydraulic and structural efficiency and reduces transverse effects,&nbsp; due to membrane forces, easily taken by transverse prestressing. <o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%">Rapid and economic construction was achieved by adopting the free cantilever method, using precast match cast epoxy glued prestressed segments, which was the latest technology at that time. It is an outstanding structure in many ways and is a major shift from traditional methods of design and construction of aqueducts. It combines aesthetics with efficiency and economy. Specially designed and fabricated lightweight equipment for construction were fabricated locally.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223610280.jpg', 'bhima-aqueduct-maharashtra', '2015-01-13 14:46:02', '2015-01-27 17:47:08', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(20, 10, 'SYPHON AQUEDUCT ON RIVER MEN, GUJARAT', '<p align="left" class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-ansi-language:EN-GB">This Syphon Aqueduct is provided where the Narmada Main Canal crosses the Men River and has a design discharge of 1560 cumecs. The Narmada Main Canal is 73.1m wide at the base, has a water depth of 7.6m and has sloping sides. At the crossing, the canal is flumed to a width of 50m and is taken over a series of 16 barrels. &nbsp;Each barrel is 7m wide and 5.03m high The foundation is in the form of an RCC raft resting on sandy strata. A meter deep portion of soil below the raft is replaced by compacted sand to serve as a uniform cushion. The raft is surrounded by an RCC diaphragm wall, which confines the soil strata. The design takes into account effects of foundation strata settlement.</span><span lang="EN-GB"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223610650.jpg', 'syphon-aqueduct-on-river-men-gujarat', '2015-01-13 14:46:56', '2015-01-27 17:47:45', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(21, 10, 'INDIRA SAGAR DAM, IRRIGATION AND HYDRO-ELECTRIC PROJECT,  MADHYA PRADESH', '<p>\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:9.0pt;font-family:\r\n&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-ansi-language:\r\nEN-GB;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">The Narmada Hydroelectric Development Corporation Limited ( joint venture of the National Hydroelectric Power Corporation and the Govt. of Madhya Pradesh) constructed the Indira Sagar Dam on the river Narmada. It is a concrete gravity dam, 653 m in length, with a maximum height of 92 m. The spillway portion of the dam consists of twenty, 20 m wide gated spillways with 21 piers. The spillway gates are of the sector type, and are lifted hydraulically. The gates are 20 m wide 17 m in height, and extend from pier to pier. Each pier is 5 m in width. Prestressed replaceable anchors are provided for the spillway gates.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n', '14223610930.jpg', 'indira-sagar-dam-irrigation-and-hydro-electric-project-madhya-pradesh', '2015-01-13 14:47:59', '2015-01-27 17:48:13', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(22, 10, 'ORSANG AQUEDUCT ON NARMADA MAIN CANAL, GUJARAT', '<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%">The Orsang River carries a maximum flood discharge of 15,235 cumecs.&nbsp; The depth of scour for piers at maximum flood discharge is 21.38 m below the HFL.&nbsp; The typical span is 20.3 m center to center of bearings. Due to the large water and concrete load, the piers are in solid RCC, 80 m in length and 2.5 m in thickness.&nbsp; They rest over pile caps which are 1.5 m thick. The structure rests on 26 piers and two abutments.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%">&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%">&nbsp;The Orsang aqueduct is one of the pioneering applications of large diameter pile foundations in which the more conventional and expensive well foundations were replaced by piles. This reduced the amount of concrete in the foundations significantly.&nbsp; Similarly, savings in materials required for the superstructure were also made.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223611130.jpg', 'orsang-aqueduct-on-narmada-main-canal-gujarat', '2015-01-13 14:49:08', '2015-01-27 17:48:33', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(23, 10, 'Management Consultancy & Technical Assistance for Water Resources Consolidation Project, Orissa', '<p>\r\n	<span style="font-size:9.0pt;font-family:&quot;Arial&quot;,&quot;sans-serif&quot;;\r\nmso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;color:#231F20;mso-ansi-language:EN-US;\r\nmso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:MR">The project primarily deals with providing support and advice to the Department of Water Resources. The assignment covers the following major water resource projects in the entire state of Orissa:&nbsp; Scheme Completion for Rengali, Mahanadi, Narej, Badanalla, Harbhangi, Hariharjore, Upper Jonk, Beghua; Selected System Improvement and Farmer Turnover for Kendrapara Canal, Sakhigopal, Rushikulya, Baitarani, Hirakud, Hiradharabati, Godahadha;&nbsp; Combined Scheme Completion and Selected System Improvement and Farmer Turnover for Mahanadi Basin and Baitarani Basin</span></p>\r\n', '14223611350.jpg', 'management-consultancy-and-technical-assistance-for-water-resources-consolidation-project-orissa', '2015-01-13 14:50:15', '2015-01-27 17:48:55', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(24, 10, 'GANDIKOTA DAM, ANDHRA PRADESH', '<p>\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:9.0pt;font-family:\r\n&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-ansi-language:\r\nEN-GB;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">Gandikota Dam is constructed in the gorge portion at the confluence of river Chitravathi and Pennar, Kadapa District, Andhra Pradesh, a part of the Galeru Nagari Sujala Sravanthi project. The main objective of the project is irrigation and flood control. Length of this Dam is 305m, height is 40.50m above foundation level, storage capacity is 760m<sup>3</sup>. The spillway is provided with 14 nos, 15.0mx9.80m radial gates to discharge design flood of 8180 cumecs. A roller bucket type energy dissipater is provided with a concrete apron. A drainage gallery relieves uplift pressure in the dam. Instrumentation has been installed to monitor performance of the dam.</span></p>\r\n', '14223611690.jpg', 'gandikota-dam-andhra-pradesh', '2015-01-13 14:51:12', '2015-01-27 17:49:29', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(25, 10, 'KOL DAM HYDROELECTRIC POWER PROJECT, HIMACHAL PRADESH', '<p>\r\n	<span lang="EN-IN" style="font-size:9.0pt;font-family:\r\n&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-ansi-language:\r\nEN-IN;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">The Kol Dam project is located on the Sutlej River, 6 km upstream of Dehar Power Station in Himachal Pradesh. It consists of a 163 m high rock fill dam, which is taken on the downstream side of the concrete portion of the dam.&nbsp; It has a power house located at the toe of the dam with an installed capacity of 4 x 200 MW. The height of the spillway is 26 m &amp; the height of the spillway weir is 49 m. The length of the spillway weir is 138.6 m with six modules of 23.1 m each. There are six radial gates of 17.1 m width x 17 m height. The dam has a maximum storage capacity of 560 x 106 m<sup>3</sup>. The penstocks from the intake chamber to the power house incorporate four parallel, approximately 8.5 m diameter, horseshoe tunnels.</span></p>\r\n', '14223611910.jpg', 'kol-dam-hydroelectric-power-project-himachal-pradesh', '2015-01-13 14:52:05', '2015-01-27 17:49:51', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(26, 10, 'GHATTARGA BARRAGE, KARNATAKA ', '<p>\r\n	<span lang="EN-GB" style="font-size:9.0pt;font-family:\r\n&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;mso-fareast-font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;;mso-ansi-language:\r\nEN-GB;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA">A submersible Bridge cum Barrage has been constructed across river Bhima near Ghattarga village, Gulbarga district, Karnataka. Length of the overflow barrage is 330m with 10m non-overflow section on left side and 90m on right side. Counter fort retaining walls are provided at the ends of the barrage. Approach roads connecting to Morartagi and Afzalpur are provided. FRL is 7m above broad crested weir level. Barrage is provided with 110 vents, 2m wide. The maximum discharge capacity of the barrage is 990 cumecs. Vertical needle type gates of size 2m x 7m are provided. Horizontal stilling basin type energy dissipater is proposed with concrete apron. Carriageway of the bridge is 7.5m.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n', '14223612270.jpg', 'ghattarga-barrage-karnataka', '2015-01-13 14:53:28', '2015-01-27 17:50:27', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(27, 10, 'REMODELING OF TUNGA BHADRA RIGHT BANK HIGH LEVEL AND POWER CANAL ', '<p align="left" class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	<span lang="EN-IN" style="font-size:9.0pt;line-height:150%;mso-ansi-language:EN-IN">Tungabhadra Right Bank High Level Canal (RBHLC) &amp; Power Canal (PC) is an interstate project between the states of Andhra Pradesh &amp; Karnataka. RBHLC and Power Canal are proposed for remodelling as there is deficiency in carrying capacity i.e. canal is unable to draw its full designed discharge. Design Discharge of RBHLC is 4000 cusecs and Power Canal is 2500 cusecs. Deficiency is observed due to ageing, seepage, silting, distortion in the canal shape due to scouring &amp; erosion, improper functioning of structures, etc. Canal Improvements such as lining and uniformity in bed width, slide slopes,&nbsp; bed fall etc. are proposed. All the structures will be checked for their hydraulic and structural adequacies.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', '14223612480.jpg', 'remodeling-of-tunga-bhadra-right-bank-high-level-and-power-canal', '2015-01-13 14:58:49', '2015-01-27 17:50:48', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(37, 5, 'Feasibility Study for 6-Laning of NH-8 from Surat to Dahisar', '<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	Preparation of the Feasibility Report for rehabilitation and up-gradation of the existing 4 lane National Highway section to 6 lane divided carriageway configuration required extensive survey work of topography, traffic, condition of structures and sub-soil conditions. The economic and financial analysis was prepared, by estimating cost of undertaking the project and the benefits, that would accrue to the users as also to the society at large. The work involved examination of environmental impact during construction &nbsp;and post implementation of the project, recommendation of mitigatory measures, &nbsp;social parameters like rehabilitation of the affected persons as well as employment generation and wealth creation.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	Completion of the feasibility study in the short time of 9 m for the National Highway Authority, helped in the early implementation of the project which was a part of Phase-V of the National Highway Development Programme.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>', '14219256480.jpg', 'feasibility-study-for-6-laning-of-nh-8-from-surat-to-dahisar', '2015-01-22 16:50:48', '2015-01-22 17:34:49', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(40, 5, 'Design Work for Pathankot to Amritsar Section of NH-15', '<p>\r\n	A length of 102 km in the heavily built-up section of NH-15 offered major challenges in execution of this work. &nbsp;Apart from design of the main carriageway, 44 km of service roads had to be developed on account of high level occupancy &nbsp; and development along the corridor. &nbsp;Six by-passes covering almost 40% of the stretch were required to be created apart from realignment of 1.6 km. Within the stretch, there were 24 major junctions and 5 Grade separators. &nbsp;Additionally the stretch had 148 Nos minor junctions and a large number of bridges (major 4 and minor 6). &nbsp;Five ROB&rsquo;s had to be designed apart from widening of 90 existing culverts and reconstruction/ &nbsp; new construction of more than 200 culverts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	As the client was a fast track contractor, services had to be provided rapidly, to match the speed of construction and design work was carried out sufficiently ahead of work in the field in proper sequence. The project earned STUP high appreciation from the Authorities and the Stakeholders.</p>', '14219284160.jpg', 'design-work-for-pathankot-to-amritsar-section-of-nh-15', '2015-01-22 17:36:56', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(38, 5, 'Road Master Plan for Bangladesh', '<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	Most areas of Bangladesh are flood plains, subject to heavy rainfall and consequent flooding. With a disjointed network and disruption by mighty rivers, road communication was one of the critical problems of the newly-born country. World Bank, Asian Development Bank and the Japanese Development Fund were keen to invest in the road network which was important to bolster the economy. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	Asian Development Bank took the lead by inviting a large consultancy assignment for creating a Road Master Plan for the entire country that would include the National Network, the Regional Roads and Major District Roads so that most areas of Bangladesh could be readily accessed by motorized road transport. ADB desired that the Road Master Plan be developed based on HDM (Highway Design Module) software, developed by the World Bank sometime earlier. This was a unique initiative as nowhere in the World had such software been used for creating a Master Plan for an entire country.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	STUP Consultants alongwith Transroute International, a French Consultant, secured this prestigious assignment against intense International competition. The team of specialists posted in the Project office at Dhaka, created through the Local Associate &ndash; Bangladesh Consultants Ltd, conducted intensive field studies with custom built equipments for assessing road conditions of 12,500 km of Roads all over the country and evaluated the restrictive effects of multiple vehicle ferry crossings that were unique to this country.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	Transport economists analyzed the effects of such traffic hold ups and worked out the benefits of the Master Plan that would accrue to the road users. All the data was fed into the HDM programme for generating an optimum road network development scheme that would be the Road Master Plan of the country, which become the basis for future road development projects for the next 20 years. Road development and road maintenance programmes of the country, formulated by abiding with the Master Plan, generated immense benefit to the economy of Bangladesh and helped &nbsp;the &nbsp;country in becoming economically self sufficient.</p>\r\n<p class="MsoBodyText">\r\n	Playing a lead role in the development of the Road Master Plan, STUP earned appreciation from International funding agencies.</p>\r\n<div>\r\n	&nbsp;</div>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal">\r\n	<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n', '14219258060.jpg', 'road-master-plan-for-bangladesh', '2015-01-22 16:53:26', '2015-01-22 17:31:33', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(41, 5, 'Construction Supervision of Ratanpur  Gandhinagar on NH8', '<p>\r\n	Rapid industrialization in the State of Gujarat, required that, four-laning of a 106 KM two-lane stretch of NH8 between Ratanpur and Gandhinagar, be taken up on priority basis.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Appointed by NHAI, STUP&rsquo;s role was to provide expert supervision and quality control of the project execution in the field. &nbsp;The project was procured against International Competitive Bidding process and executed under FIDIC conditions of contract. This was one of the first projects in India to use state-of-art machinery and equipment on Road projects. The project included two major bridges across wide rivers, flyovers, ROB and cross drainage structures. Work also included construction of a bypass, Toll Plaza, drainage, way-side amenities and stabilization of existing embankments. &nbsp;Training of workmen for quality control and for ensuring safety during construction was a part of the assignment</p>', '14219284830.jpg', 'construction-supervision-of-ratanpur-gandhinagar-on-nh8', '2015-01-22 17:38:03', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(39, 5, 'Local Roads Improvement Project in Indonesia', '<p>\r\n	STUP won this prestigious ADB funded project, after keen competition from International Consultants from the developed countries based on Quality of their proposal. The project was a part of the 9th Road Maintenance Sector project for Indonesia implemented by Bina Marga, Ministry of Public Works, Indonesia.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The work included screening and feasibility study for improvement of local roads in 46 Kabupatens (districts) in the provinces of Central Java, Yogyakarta and East Java. The scope included socio economic review, data collection, traffic and condition surveys, environmental impact and mitigation, and evaluation of benefits.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	With efficient implementation of this assignment, the studies were extended to cover 24 more Kabupatens in Central Java and East Java thus covering 45,000 km of road in 70 districts in three provinces. &nbsp;A new technique was developed to select candidate links for improvement. &nbsp;Recommendations were made regarding, equipment selection and institutional development for effective implementation. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The Project provided STUP an opportunity for interaction with a major local consulting organization, P T Yodya Karya. This land mark project in Indonesia helped STUP in developing cordial relations with various stakeholders in the country and opened doors for more work in S.E. Asia.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>', '14219259950.jpg', 'local-roads-improvement-project-in-indonesia', '2015-01-22 16:56:35', '2015-01-22 17:35:34', '1', '', '', '', 0),
(60, 3, '01REACTOR BUILDINGS FOR THE ATOMIC POWER PLANTS (2X235MW), MADRAS ', '<p>\r\n	The reactor buildings have a double containment: the inner prestressed &nbsp;concrete &nbsp;containment &nbsp;is 610 mm thick, 39.6 m diameter and 42.6m height and the outer containment is a reinforced stone masonry free standing shell 710 mm thick. It provides a second barrier and additional radiation protection. The inner prestressed concrete containment covered with 5 coats of PVC paint on the inside provides a leak tight environment which can withstand internal pressures and temperatures during an MCA. The annular space &nbsp;between &nbsp;the containments is maintained &nbsp;below &nbsp;atmospheric pressure (- 0.2 Atmospheres) &nbsp;to aspirate any leakage from the inner shell in the event of an MCA.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	This structure, conceived in 1967, is the world&rsquo;s first double containment system. After MAPP, many countries have adopted the Double Containment System as it provides the highest security against radioactivity.&nbsp;</p>', '14219307390.jpg', '01reactor-buildings-for-the-atomic-power-plants-(2x235mw)-madras', '2015-01-22 18:15:39', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(61, 3, '2 X 235 MW ATOMIC  POWER  PLANTS,  AT NARORA,  UTTAR  PRADESH  (NAPP 1&2) ', '<p>\r\n	The double containment concept developed for MAPP was taken further in the nuclear reactors at Narora. This was achieved by restricting the inner prestressed concrete &nbsp;container to the radioactive source of energy. The other source of energy, the steam generators, were placed outside in the RCC containment. The slab separating the high pressure space (when there is a Maximum Credible Nuclear Accident) was designed as a cellular grid. Independent safety valves in the outer containment called blow out panels, for boiler related accidents, eliminate high pressure rise in the second containment. Further, the annular space between the containments and the voids in the slab are permanently maintained &nbsp;at a negative pressure in order to minimize the danger of radioactive gases leaking into the atmosphere.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Instead of a single protective layer above the radio-active source, this design has a complete double containment.</p>', '14219309290.jpg', '2-x-235-mw-atomic-power-plants-at-narora-uttar-pradesh-(napp-1and2)', '2015-01-22 18:18:49', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(43, 5, 'Detailed Project Report for 1300 km Rural Roads under PMGSY Scheme', '<p>\r\n	Pradhan Mantri Gram Sadak Yojana (PMGSY) is an iconic project for connecting every habitation of upto 250 persons in the country with a motorable road network, and designed to improve the &nbsp;mobility and connectivity of the vast rural population.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	STUP was entrusted with the preparation of detailed project report along with drawings covering alignment plan, pavement design, cross drainage structures, and cost estimates for 1250 km roads, through hilly terrains of Tripura. Work included more than 220 links in the districts of North Tripura and Dhalai, in areas with security risk, arising from cases of insurgency. More than 350 km of road were upgraded apart from new construction of 950 km. One of the challenges was achieving proper road geometry in terrain with steep gradients.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Some of the serious challenges were land acquisition, heavy rainfall, weak soil strata, scarcity of construction materials. &nbsp;STUP carried out extensive reconnaissance of the existing alignment and extensive investigations. Innovative solutions to overcome the challenges were provided during implementation.</p>', '14219287900.jpg', 'detailed-project-report-for-1300-km-rural-roads-under-pmgsy-scheme', '2015-01-22 17:43:10', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(44, 5, 'Mumbai-Pune Expressway', '<p>\r\n	Mumbai-Pune Expressway, a Greenfield six lane access controlled freeway, &nbsp;with two intermediate interchanges, &nbsp;is a landmark project that created wide awareness of the benefits of the expressway system among the Indian urban population for the first time. &nbsp;Linking of two major urban centers free from interfering traffic, benefited users immensely by reduction to half the travel time leading to fuel savings, reduced accidents and environmental gains.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	STUP, as the Consultant handling the difficult 14 km stretch starting from Panvel, near Mumbai, contributed greatly to the success of this project. STUP&rsquo;s assignment included finalizing the alignment and geometric design, design of the rigid concrete pavement, bridges, underpass and overpass, planning of drainage and signage. &nbsp;Starting with topographical survey and geotechnical investigations, work included the detail engineering, preparation of tender documents, cost estimates, scrutiny and evaluation of tenders and construction supervision, quality Assurance and project management. This expressway, through western ghat hilly areas, stands as a testimony to engineering excellence in the highway sector of the country.</p>', '14219288590.jpg', 'mumbai-pune-expressway', '2015-01-22 17:44:19', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(45, 5, 'Expressways at Haza Al Maqam, Al Ain, UAE', '<p>\r\n	The Haza Al Maqam Expressways was a prestigious project in the initial days of development in United Arab Emirates. The 135 km long road network, mostly through desert landscape, was divided into 22 sectors for fast implementation. STUP&rsquo;s scope of work included planning and designing of the Road Network, segregating vehicular and pedestrian movement, design of intersections and parking facilities, designing of sidewalk and shoulders and the cross drainage structures.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	With an eye to the future, development needs were also planned, both in terms of user requirement and environmental facilities. The planning could cope with the rapid growth that the region faced with fast economic development that came from deployment of oil wealth in infrastructure expansion.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Work was carried out for the Al Ain Municipality.</p>\r\n', '14219289390.jpg', 'expressways-at-haza-al-maqam-al-ain-uae', '2015-01-22 17:45:39', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(46, 5, 'Detailed Engineering Design Services for design and construction of Eastern Freeway in Mumbai', '<p>\r\n	Eastern Freeway is a Road link in Mumbai that connects Fort area in South Mumbai to the Eastern Express Highway at Ghatkopar. This 17 km long, access controlled Freeway reduces the travel time considerably making an important change in lifestyle of commuters to the mainland area from the Southern tip of the peninsula that forms the City.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The road link has been built by Mumbai Metropolitan Region Development Authority with partial funding from the Central Government through the JNNURM scheme. The Freeway has 11.5 km Elevated Road and 4.3 km Road-Tunnel.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	STUP&rsquo;s responsibility included detailed engineering services for the 11.5 km long 4 lanes elevated road section linking Princes Dock area and Anik Bus depot in Wadala. Four exit and entry ramps also form part of the assignment.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Built on areas having multiple underground utilities, the support location had to be adjusted to suit the site requirements Superstructure spans varied from 30 to 45 m, built with prestressed concrete segmental box girders installed with launching girders. The foundation construction was with piles and the sub-structure in reinforced concrete. The main challenge was to align all elements of the structure to suit the geometric configurations of this high speed freeway and to design the same.</p>', '14219290130.jpg', 'detailed-engineering-design-services-for-design-and-construction-of-eastern-freeway-in-mumbai', '2015-01-22 17:46:53', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(47, 5, 'P.V.N.R. Elevated Corridor at Hyderabad (11.67 km) Long.', '<p>\r\n	This Elevated Expressway of 11.67 km length which connects the central business district of the city with NH 7 includes a trumpet interchange for the approach road to the International Airport, and was the longest in India at its time of construction. The length comprises a viaduct section of 11.4 km, a toll plaza section of 393 m, and 200 m length of ramps of the main flyover. The width of the carriageway is 17.2 m</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The project basically comprises of a) Construction of 4 lane divided carriageway with median of 1.2 m from Sarojini Eye Hospital, Mehedipatnam to Aramgarh junction on NH-7 (along ring road) along with main / intermediate ramps and underpass at Aramgarh junction b) Construction of Trumpet interchangeon NH-7 for the approach road to the International Airport and c) Strengthening, widening of Inner Ring Road (from Rethibowli junction to Aramgarh junction from 4- lane to 6- lane</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Work &nbsp; scope as Constructor&rsquo;s Consultant including detailed design and drawings, construction scheme and analysis, electrification and illumination drawings, Bill of Quantities and As-built Drawings.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Simply supported post-tensioned box girders were used, with length of span being optimized at 35 m centre of piers except where otherwise needed from obligatory conditions. Expansion joints were provided at 140 m intervals. </p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Segmental construction was adopted, the segments being match cast in yards, transported, assembled on a launching girder, stressed for joining together spans. This saved interference with traffic and therefore construction time. The work was completed in three years.</p>', '14219290720.jpg', 'p-v-n-r-elevated-corridor-at-hyderabad-(11-67-km)-long', '2015-01-22 17:47:52', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(48, 6, 'Cable Stayed Bridge across river Mapusa at Aldona, Goa, India', '<p>\r\n	It is a 235 m long, 2 lane cable stayed bridge with main span 105m and single pylon of 34 m height (from deck) designed for class 70 R loading with fatigue, seismic and aerodynamic effects. &nbsp;The anchor span of 80m to the main span has been provided and one approach span of 25 m with PSC girders has been constructed. The pylons are in concrete and the stiffening girder is composite with Steel I &ndash; girders and concrete deck. The pylon below the deck is formed into an &ldquo;A&rdquo; frame for better stability and supported on a pile foundation. The bridge was commissioned in 2004 for public use.</p>\r\n', '14219293370.jpg', 'cable-stayed-bridge-across-river-mapusa-at-aldona-goa-india', '2015-01-22 17:52:17', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0),
(49, 6, 'Third Karnaphuli Bridge over river Karnaphuli between Chittangong and Cox Bazar, Bangladesh', '<p>\r\n	The Third Karnaphuli Bridge Project on National Highway No.-1 connecting Chittangong to Cox Bazar being constructed with the assistance of Kuwait Fund Loan No. 704, 50m up stream of existing Shah Amanat Shah Steel Bridge.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The main bridge with viaduct of 950 m in length is constructed as a multi-span extradosed concrete precast segmental superstructure of span 200mhaving 2way 6 lanes carriageway with a central median and 1.5 m wide pedestrian footpaths on each side - thus total width of the deck will be 24.4 m. The bridge had to be constructed to a curve in plan and in vertical profile.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The other related works involve: River Training Works, including bank protection, Toll Plaza, Control Building, minor drainage structures etc. An approach length 1450 m and service road of 2500m, a computerized toll collection system and related electrical and mechanical works are also included.</p>', '14219294580.jpg', 'third-karnaphuli-bridge-over-river-karnaphuli-between-chittangong-and-cox-bazar-bangladesh', '2015-01-22 17:54:18', NULL, '1', '', '', '', 0);
